# EU Copyright Reproduction and Extraction Rights

## Legal Framework Overview

| Directive | Key Articles | What It Protects | Relevance to AI Systems |
|---|---|---|---|
| InfoSoc Directive 2001/29/EC | Arts. 2, 3, 5 | Reproduction + communication to the public | Any copying of text/images into AI pipelines |
| Database Directive 96/9/EC | Arts. 7, 8 | Sui generis database right | Extracting substantial parts of structured databases |
| Software Directive 2009/24/EC | Arts. 4, 6 | Software source/object code | Decompilation, code analysis |
| DSM Directive 2019/790 | Arts. 3, 4, 17 | TDM exception + opt-out | AI training and inference on third-party content |
| Rental and Lending Directive 2006/115/EC | Art. 9 | Distribution right | Sharing copies of ingested documents |

---

## 📚 InfoSoc Directive 2001/29/EC

### Article 2 — Reproduction Right

**What is protected:** Any direct or indirect, temporary or permanent reproduction of a work by any means and in any form, in whole or in part.

**In the context of AI systems this means:**

- **PROHIBITED without license/exception**: Loading a PDF into a vector database (permanent reproduction)
- **PROHIBITED without license/exception**: Storing extracted text from a copyrighted document
- **PROHIBITED without license/exception**: Including copyrighted text verbatim in LLM prompts
- **MAY BE PERMITTED**: Temporary RAM copies made as part of a lawful transmission (Art. 5(1) transient copies exception)
- **MAY BE PERMITTED**: Extraction of factual, non-creative elements (facts are not protected — CJEU *Infopaq* C-5/08)

### Rules for AI Development

- **RULE**: Never store the full text of a copyrighted document in any persistent database
- **RULE**: Temporary copies for the purpose of text extraction and analysis may qualify under Art. 5(1) — but only if transient and technically necessary
- **RULE**: Extracted factual content (prices, thresholds, dates, transaction rules) is not protected — only creative expression is
- **RULE**: Verbatim reproduction of even a small portion (11 words sufficient under *Infopaq*) constitutes reproduction

### Article 3 — Communication to the Public Right

**What is protected:** Any communication to the public of works, including making works available so they can be accessed from a place and time individually chosen.

**In the context of AI systems:**

- **PROHIBITED**: Displaying verbatim excerpts from copyrighted documents in API responses
- **PROHIBITED**: Returning verbatim text in AI-generated summaries without license
- **PERMITTED**: Communicating factual information derived from a document (e.g., "the annual fee is €1,200")
- **PERMITTED**: Paraphrased summaries that convey factual content without reproducing expression

### Article 5 — Exceptions and Limitations

**Permitted uses relevant to AI systems:**

| Exception | Article | Conditions |
|---|---|---|
| Transient/incidental copies | Art. 5(1) | Technically necessary, no independent economic significance |
| Research and private study | Art. 5(3)(a) | Non-commercial, to the extent justified |
| Quotation for criticism/review | Art. 5(3)(d) | Short excerpt, proper attribution, for commentary |
| TDM for research | DSM Art. 3 | Research organisations only (see TDM guidelines) |
| TDM for any purpose | DSM Art. 4 | No opt-out present (see TDM guidelines) |

**None of these exceptions permit:**
- Full document reproduction in a persistent store
- Verbatim text output in commercial AI-generated content
- Redistribution of copyrighted content to third parties

